doc.ContractDescription: MANY TROPICAL COUNTRIES ARE NOW WORKING ON DEVELOPING THEIR STRATEGIES FOR REDUCING EMISSIONS FROM DEFORESTATION AND FOREST DEGRADATION, INCLUDING ACTIVITIES THAT RESULT IN CONSERVATION OR ENHANCEMENT OF FOREST CARBON STOCKS AND SUSTAINABLE MANAGEMENT OF FORESTS, (REDD+) TO EFFECTIVELY DECREASE FOREST-BASED EMISSIONS. A NEW INTERNATIONAL REDD+ AGREEMENT IS AT THE HEART OF RECENT NEGOTIATIONS OF THE PARTIES TO THE UN FRAMEWORK CONVENTION ON CLIMATE CHANGE (UNFCCC). REDD+ MECHANISMS COULD PROVIDE AN OPPORTUNITY TO NOT ONLY DIMINISH AN IMPORTANT SOURCE OF EMISSIONS, BUT ALSO TO PROMOTE LARGE-SCALE COMPREHENSIVE CONSERVATION OF TROPICAL FORESTS AND ESTABLISH INCENTIVES AND OPPORTUNITIES TO REDUCE DEFORESTATION WHILE ALLEVIATING POVERTY. MOST OF THESE COUNTRIES STILL LACK BASIC INFORMATION FOR DEVELOPING AND IMPLEMENTING THEIR CARBON ASSESSMENT AND EVALUATING IMPACTS OF REDD+ ASSOCIATED POLICIES, SUCH AS THE EXTENT OF FOREST AREA, THE RATE AT WHICH FORESTS ARE BEING CLEARED AND/OR DEGRADED, AND THE CARBON AMOUNTS ASSOCIATED WITH THESE LOSSES. THESE COUNTRIES ALSO NEED SUPPORT IN CONDUCTING INTEGRATED ASSESSMENTS OF THE MOST PROMISING APPROACHES FOR REDUCING EMISSIONS, AND IN IDENTIFYING THOSE POLICY OPTIONS THAT HOLD THE GREATEST POTENTIAL. THE EAST AFRICA SERVIR HUB CAN BE PIVOTAL IN HELPING TO PROVIDE THESE DATA SETS TO COUNTRIES VIA BEST PRACTICE TOOLS AND METHODS TO SUPPORT COST EFFECTIVE FOREST CARBON MONITORING SOLUTIONS AND MORE INFORMED DECISION MAKING PROCESSES UNDER REDD+. THE PROPOSED WORK WITH SERVIR WILL ADDRESS KEY QUESTIONS ABOUT CARBON ASSESSMENT AND MANAGEMENT IN ONE OF THE RICHEST REGIONS OF BIOLOGICAL DIVERSITY IN AFRICA. CARBON STOCKS HAVE BEEN HIGHLY DEPLETED DUE TO THE HIGH DEMAND FOR AGRICULTURAL LAND AND FUEL WOOD CONSUMPTION FROM A GROWING POPULATION. HIGH CARBON DENSITY FORESTS ARE MAINLY FOUND IN ISOLATED PROTECTED AREAS OR MOUNTAIN REGIONS AND HAVE LOST CONNECTIVITY. WE WILL DEMONSTRATE THAT NASA EARTH SCIENCE PRODUCTS AND DERIVED MODELS CAN ASSIST COUNTRIES WITH THEIR TERRESTRIAL CARBON ASSESSMENT AND FOREST CONSERVATION STRATEGY BY: 1) ESTABLISHING FOREST CARBON STOCK BASELINES, ASSESSING HISTORICAL AND CURRENT CARBON EMISSIONS FROM DEFORESTATION AND DEGRADATION AND ENABLING COUNTRIES TO MONITOR AND PREDICT THE EFFECTS OF NATURAL RESOURCE POLICIES AND EFFORTS TO MITIGATE NEGATIVE IMPACTS OF LAND USE AND LAND USE CHANGE. 2) IDENTIFYING CORRIDORS OF HIGH FOREST CARBON STOCK TO BE PRESERVED AND POTENTIAL AREAS TO BE REPLANTED IN ORDER TO CONNECT PARKS AND PROTECTED AREAS AND SUSTAIN BIOLOGICAL DIVERSITY. 3) TRAINING AND BUILDING CAPACITY IN THE USE OF MAPS, TOOLS AND MODELS TO BE DEVELOPED AS PART OF THIS PROJECT WITH OUR COLLABORATORS IN THE SERVIR COUNTRIES THROUGH ANNUAL WORKSHOPS FOR PARK AND FOREST MANAGERS AND LOCAL AND INTERNATIONAL NGOS. OUTCOMES OF THE PROJECT WILL DEMONSTRATE PRACTICAL SOLUTIONS FOR NATIONAL AND LOCAL CARBON ASSESSMENT AND REDD+ IMPLEMENTATION AND WILL ASSIST COUNTRIES IN IDENTIFYING APPROPRIATE POLICIES TO ACHIEVE SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT GOALS THROUGH SCENARIO MODELING (SOARES-FILHO ET AL., 2010) AND DETERMINATION OF WHERE CARBON EMISSIONS COULD BE MINIMIZED. THE WOODS HOLE RESEARCH CENTER (WHRC) HAS A LONG HISTORY OF WORKING ON CARBON MODELING (HOUGHTON, 2005), FOREST MONITORING (LAPORTE ET AL., 2007) AND CARBON MAPPING (BACCINI ET AL., 2008; GOETZ ET AL., 2009) AND ALSO IN PROVIDING SCIENCE-BASED RESULTS TO DECISION MAKERS (GREENGLASS, 2011; STICKLER ET AL., 2009; CATTANEO, 2011; SOARES-FILHO, 2010; LAPORTE ET AL, 2008). THE WHRC WILL COORDINATE ITS WORK WITH THE SERVIR TEAM LEAD. WHRC WILL ALSO HELP SERVIR REACH ITS OVERALL OBJECTIVE OF STRENGTHENING MONITORING SYSTEMS USING EARTH OBSERVATIONS TO SUPPORT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND ADAPTATION TO CLIMATE CHANGE THROUGH ITS EXTENDED NETWORK OF COLLABORATORS IN EIGHT SERVIR COUNTRIES THAT ARE CURRENTLY ENGAGED IN CARBON MAPPING ACTIVITIES WITH THE WHRC.
